<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[264,1325,284,1430]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis box="[312,414,1324,1349]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[429,508,1324,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kirti">
<emphasis box="[429,508,1324,1349]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. kirti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[640,749,1324,1349]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="knappi">
<emphasis box="[640,749,1324,1349]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. knappi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs in the structure of the paraphyses and in having a stouter aedeagal shaft. Each paraphyses is separate right from the base whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[294,374,1404,1429]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="knappi">
<emphasis box="[294,374,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">knappi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are fused for a distance at the base before separating.
</paragraph>
